Generics

Generics enable creating reusable components that work with a variety of types rather than a single one.

### Why Generics?

Without generics, you'd need to use `any` (losing type safety) or duplicate code for each type.

```typescript
// Without generics - any loses type safety
function identity(arg: any): any {
  return arg;
}

// With generics - type safe
function identity<T>(arg: T): T {
  return arg;
}
```

### Generic Functions

```typescript
function firstElement<T>(arr: T[]): T | undefined {
  return arr[0];
}

const first = firstElement([1, 2, 3]); // type: number | undefined
```

### Generic Interfaces

```typescript
interface Repository<T> {
  getById(id: number): T | undefined;
  getAll(): T[];
  create(item: T): void;
  update(id: number, item: T): void;
  delete(id: number): void;
}

class UserRepo implements Repository<User> {
  // Must implement all methods with User type
}
```

### Generic Type Aliases

```typescript
type Result<T> = {
  success: true;
  data: T;
} | {
  success: false;
  error: string;
};

type ApiResponse<T> = {
  status: number;
  data: T;
  message: string;
};
```

### Type Parameter Naming

| Parameter | Convention |
|-----------|-----------|
| T | Type |
| K | Key |
| V | Value |
| E | Element |
| R | Return type |

> **Key Point:** Generics provide compile-time type safety while allowing runtime flexibility.

codeExample:
// Generic identity function
function identity<T>(arg: T): T {
  return arg;
}

// Generic array wrapper
function wrapInArray<T>(item: T): T[] {
  return [item];
}

const numArr = wrapInArray(42); // number[]
const strArr = wrapInArray("hello"); // string[]

// Generic interface
interface KeyValuePair<K, V> {
  key: K;
  value: V;
}

const entry: KeyValuePair<string, number> = {
  key: "age",
  value: 30
};

// Generic with default type
function createArray<T = string>(length: number, value: T): T[] {
  return Array(length).fill(value);
}

const arr = createArray(3, "default"); // string[]
